    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To strengthen the affirmative side's case for increased border security, your team can emphasize the economic benefits of controlling a porous border, drawing parallels with other successful border management models like East Germany's strict division and reunification. They can also argue that enhanced border security is a means to protect American workers, particularly those in low-skilled and high-skilled occupations, from the negative impacts of an open border, such as increased competition for jobs and downward pressure on wages. This can be supported by citing studies on the negative effects of immigration on low-skilled workers in European countries like the UK and Germany, which illustrates that overly lax immigration controls can have far-reaching consequences for societal cohesion. Moreover, proponents can also highlight the role of border security in addressing issues like human trafficking and organized crime.",
